<h2><span class="mw-headline" id="Notes">Notes</span></h2>
<div class="reflist" style="list-style-type: decimal;">
<ol class="references">
<li id="cite_note-2"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-2">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">6th Airborne landed 7,220 men, 17th Airborne landed 9,650 men.<sup id="cite_ref-Ellis.2C_p._291_1-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Ellis.2C_p._291-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-4"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-4">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Otway claims that Allied intelligence placed 7 Parachute Division and 84 Infantry Division at around 4,000 men each after having suffered heavy casualties in previous campaigns, these being the two German formations facing the Allied airborne forces.<sup id="cite_ref-Otway_299_3-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Otway_299-3"><span>[</span>2<span>]</span></a></sup></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-6"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-6">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Ellis puts 6th Airborne losses as 1,400 dead, wounded or captured and places the 17th Airborne losses as 1,300 dead, wounded or captured.<sup id="cite_ref-Ellis.2C_p._291_1-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Ellis.2C_p._291-1"><span>[</span>1<span>]</span></a></sup> The official British Parachute Regiment website places 6th Airborne losses at 1,078 killed or wounded.<sup id="cite_ref-5" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-5"><span>[</span>3<span>]</span></a></sup></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-8"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-8">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Over 1,700 aircraft were employed during the airlift of the airborne forces, of which 56 planes were lost. A further 240 planes flew a resupply mission following the glider landings, 16 planes were shot down. Of the 1,300 gliders employed during the operation, under 4% were destroyed.<sup id="cite_ref-7" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-7"><span>[</span>4<span>]</span></a></sup></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-13"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-13">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">The airborne component of <a href="/wiki/Operation_Market_Garden" title="Operation Market Garden">Operation <i>Market Garden</i></a> was a larger operation, but the drop zones were split over three distinct areas and spread over several days. Operation <i>Varsity</i> was conducted on a single day in one location, and as such, is the largest single airborne operation in history.<sup id="cite_ref-Devlin615_9-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Devlin615-9"><span>[</span>5<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-10" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-10"><span>[</span>6<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-11" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-11"><span>[</span>7<span>]</span></a></sup><sup id="cite_ref-12" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-12"><span>[</span>8<span>]</span></a></sup></span></li>
<li id="cite_note-65"><span class="mw-cite-backlink"><b><a href="#cite_ref-65">^</a></b></span> <span class="reference-text">Brereton recommended a daylight operation because in his judgment Luftwaffe fighter opposition by day, consisting of a handful of jets, was less a threat than the German night-fighter force. Also, conditions at four of the nine glider-mission airfields on the continent made them unsuitable for glider operations at night.<sup id="cite_ref-Warren160-161_22-1" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-Warren160-161-22"><span>[</span>17<span>]</span></a></sup></span></li>
</ol>
</div>
